{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"405ffd5b-6fe6-4911-bc38-09f8bb8c4c74","content":"On macOS, the system automatically generates crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Crash reports** are saved to:\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nLook for files named `<YourApp>-<date>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS). You can also browse them in **Console.app** → *Crash Reports*.\n\n**Core dumps** (for deeper debugging) are disabled by default. To enable them:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nThen reproduce the crash. The core file will appear in `/cores/` (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n> **Tip:** If `/cores/` doesn't exist, create it with `sudo mkdir /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ab636273-490c-4bc8-a29f-f7da51feb7d6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.\n\nOn macOS, when a process crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Here's what they need to know:\n\n1. **macOS Crash Reports** are stored in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user processes) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system processes).\n2. The files are named like `<ProcessName>-<date>-<time>.ips` (newer macOS) or `.crash` (older macOS).\n\n\n3. They can also access these reports through Console.app under the Crash Reports section.\n4. For core dumps specifically, macOS stores them in `/cores/` but they're disabled by default — enabling them requires running `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching the app.","outputTokens":446,"requestId":"D81B:2749A7:6137FF5:691B427:69FBF022"},"id":"5d7804d5-3f8a-4f12-8911-7fa39f332c3f","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:51:41.311Z","parentId":"435ddd8b-bd80-480e-837a-87c6b9069569"}
